prompt:
I'm putting together a sokoban practice tool for our puzzle club and I need the engine underneath it — the UI comes later, this ticket is only the rules core. C++20, stdlib only, files sokoban.h and sokoban.cpp, exposing exactly:

    struct Sokoban { /* your representation */ };

    bool sb_load(Sokoban *s, const std::string &level);
    int  sb_move(Sokoban *s, char dir);
    int  sb_run(Sokoban *s, const std::string &lurd);
    bool sb_undo(Sokoban *s);
    bool sb_solved(const Sokoban *s);
    bool sb_deadlocked(const Sokoban *s);
    int  sb_moves(const Sokoban *s);
    int  sb_pushes(const Sokoban *s);
    std::string sb_render(const Sokoban *s);

Levels come in the standard text format, one row per line ('\n'-separated): '#' wall, ' ' floor, '.' goal, '$' box, '*' box on a goal, '@' player, '+' player on a goal. Lines may be ragged — pad short lines with floor to the widest line. sb_load returns false (and the object is unusable) unless there is exactly one player and the box count equals the goal count with at least one of each.

Moves are LURD letters l/u/r/d, case-insensitive. sb_move returns 2 for a push, 1 for a plain walk, 0 when the move is blocked (wall ahead, or a box with a wall, another box, or the grid edge behind it — nothing changes), and -1 for a character that isn't a move letter. sb_run applies letters left to right and stops at the first result that isn't a walk or push, returning how many moves it applied. Blocked and invalid moves never enter the history.

sb_undo reverses the most recent applied move — walking the player back and, if it was a push, pulling the box back — and returns false when there's nothing left to undo. sb_moves/sb_pushes count the applied moves (pushes included in both) currently in effect: undo decrements them.

sb_solved: every box on a goal. sb_deadlocked: some box sits on a NON-goal square that is cornered — at least one wall (or grid edge) directly above or below it, AND at least one wall (or grid edge) directly to its left or right. A box on a goal never counts, no matter how walled-in.

sb_render returns the board in the same text format, every row exactly grid-width wide and terminated with '\n', using '*' and '+' for the on-goal cases.

The suite in test_sokoban.cpp fixes six little levels with exact renders, return codes, counters, deadlock verdicts and a full undo-to-start round trip. make test is the gate; hands off test_sokoban.cpp, mintest.h and the Makefile.
